body:
Using ```GetPeerRef()``` with an encapsulated lock for ```m_peer_map```, then manually locking the private mutex 3 lines later looks strange. It also requires two locks... all the drawbacks of mutex encapsulation without exploiting the benefits :)

Since misbehavior changes to the peer will go unobserved after this point anyway, why not just take and remove with a single lock?

Something like (untested):
```c++
PeerRef PeerManager::RemovePeer(NodeId id)
{
    PeerRef ret;
    {
        LOCK(m_peer_mutex);
        auto it = m_peer_map.find(id);
        if (it != m_peer_map.end()) {
            ret = std::move(it->second);
            m_peer_map.erase(it);
        }
    }
    return ret;
}
```

